    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Due to suppression of immune system, patients with or recently recovered from cancer, are susceptible to COVID-19 [16,17]. In the one hand, the effect of fasting on suppressing immune system remains unclear [14,15] and on the other hand recent review study reveals the positive effect of fasting during Ramadan on treatment of cancer [18]. Further confirmed protocols and guidelines must produce to clarify the status of fasting or not fasting for Muslims.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 115,
                    "end": 117,
                    "mention": "16",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                },
                {
                    "start": 118,
                    "end": 120,
                    "mention": "17",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF16"
                },
                {
                    "start": 208,
                    "end": 210,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF13"
                },
                {
                    "start": 211,
                    "end": 213,
                    "mention": "15",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                },
                {
                    "start": 335,
                    "end": 337,
                    "mention": "18",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF17"
                }
            ],
            "section": "COVID-19, cancer patients and upcoming Ramadan",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Beginning of the Ramadan is considered for reducing smoking among Muslims. However, only little studies have shown the effect of smoking on increasing the chance of COVID-19 [19], more studies are needed in this regard.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 175,
                    "end": 177,
                    "mention": "19",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF18"
                }
            ],
            "section": "COVID-19, smoker Muslims and upcoming Ramadan",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "A recent study revealed that, due to the treatment protocol, patients with hypertension, or diabetes, who are treated with ACE2-increasing drugs, are at higher risk for severe COVID-19 infection [20]. Due to the effect of fasting on Diabetes, Blood fat and Hypertension, rigorous studies are needed to find the effect of fasting on reducing/increasing the chance of a healthy person to becoming ill.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 196,
                    "end": 198,
                    "mention": "20",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF19"
                }
            ],
            "section": "COVID-19, Muslims with diabetes, high blood fat, hypertension, etc. and upcoming Ramadan",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
